04377nam a22005895i 9780822389583DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223895837 a10.1515/97808223895832doi  a(DE-B1597)552324  a(OCoLC)654969754  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ18.U5bC36 2007 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a306.76/4089009732221 aCarter, Julian B, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Heart of Whiteness :bNormal Sexuality and Race in America, 1880-1940 /cJulian B Carter. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (230 p.) :b1 photo, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Search for Norma -- t1. ''Barbarians Are Not Nervous'' -- t2. The Marriage Crisis -- t3. Birds, Bees, and the Future of the Race: Making Whiteness Normal -- tEpilogue: Regarding Racial/Erotic Politics -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this groundbreaking study, Julian Carter demonstrates that between 1880 and 1940, cultural discourses of whiteness and heterosexuality fused to form a new concept of the "normal" American. Gilded Age elites defined white civilization as the triumphant achievement of exceptional people hewing to a relational ethic of strict self-discipline for the common good. During the early twentieth century, that racial and relational ideal was reconceived in more inclusive terms as "normality," something toward which everyone should strive. The appearance of inclusiveness helped make "normality" appear consistent with the self-image of a racially diverse republic; nonetheless, "normality" was gauged largely in terms of adherence to erotic and emotional conventions that gained cultural significance through their association with arguments for the legitimacy of white political and social dominance. At the same time, the affectionate, reproductive heterosexuality of "normal" married couples became increasingly central to legitimate membership in the nation.Carter builds her intricate argument from detailed readings of an array of popular texts, focusing on how sex education for children and marital advice for adults provided significant venues for the dissemination of the new ideal of normality. She concludes that because its overt concerns were love, marriage, and babies, normality discourse facilitated white evasiveness about racial inequality. The ostensible focus of "normality" on matters of sexuality provided a superficially race-neutral conceptual structure that whites could and did use to evade engagement with the unequal relations of power that continue to shape American life today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aHeterosexualityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMarriagezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRace awarenesszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSexual ethicszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial norms. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389583zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822389583.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles